This tidy dataset contains 1599 rows of data representing 1599 different Portugeuse “Vinho Verde” red wines. One of the variables is “quality” which is rated between 0 and 10. The number on each wine is rated by at least 3 wine experts. The other 11 variables are chemical attributes of the wine. More information can be found at: https://s3.amazonaws.com/udacity-hosted-downloads/ud651/wineQualityInfo.txt

I am to find how each chemical attribute influence the quality of red wines.

The average quality rating is 5.636, the median is 6, and the mode is 5. This shows that quality is a bit right skewed because the median > mean.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

Since I don’t know anything about red wine or the attributes about good or bad wine, it is hard to say.

I would assume that anything to do with taste would have an effect on quality. By reading the variable dictionary in the link provided, this includes: volatile acidity, citric acid, residual sugar, chlorides, total sulfur dioxide, and alcohol.

Bivariate Plots Section

We see a negative correlation between volatile.acid with quality and a weak positive correlation between citric.acid and quality. There is a moderate correlation between alcohol and quality and sulphates and quality. Note that this means that as alcohol percent increases, quality tends to increase. The spearman correlation coefficient measures monotonic relationships instead of linear with pearson’s correlation coefficient.

Some of the correlations we see above is as expected. There is a moderate negative correlation between citric.acid and pH. This means that as citric.acid increases, the pH goes down. This makes sense because a lower pH means that the solution is more acidic.We observe a moderate-strong negative correlation between fixed.acidity and pH. There is a strange weak positive correlation between volatile acidity and pH. This is most likely due to having a higher pH compared to fixed.acidity and citric.acid. There is a strong positive correlation between fixed.acidity and citric.acid with a weak negative correlation between fixed.acidity and volatile.acidity.

In general, these three acidic variables are a bit correlated with two of them being weakly or moderate-weakly correlated with quality. It may be more sightful to examine them further.

We see the relationship between these 3 acids more clearly above. When fixed.acidity increases, volatile.acidity decreases while citric.acid increases. When volatile.acidity increases, citric.acid tends to decrease. This lines up with the previous observation because it is the same thing as saying that when fixed.acidity decreases, volatile.acidity increases while citric.acid decreases because fixed.acidity decreases.

Due to a lack of domain knowledge, it is not clear if this is by coincidence or that when one decreases, the other one naturally increases.

It does make sense that when volatile.acidity increases, quality goes down because the taste of vinegar is stronger.

Since quality is divided into 3,4,5,6,7,8 with the mode/median at 5/6, it could be useful to create a new variable for know if a wine is low quality, medium quality, or high quality based on these values. This could lead to more interesting visualizations when this new variable is an ordered factor.

df$quality.type <- ifelse(df$quality > 6, 'High', ifelse(df$quality > 4,
                                                         'Medium', 'Low'))
df$quality.type <- factor(df$quality.type, levels = c('Low', 'Medium', 'High'))

Wine quality increases drastically when total sulfur dioxide content is at 280-290, though this could just be outliers. Wine quality at 160 total sulfur dioxide is about the same as when there is around 10-40 total sulfur dioxide in the wine. The wines with between 40-160 total sulfur dioxide have the lowest quality with the lowest at 120. Using median as the measure, wines appear to have higher quality when total sulfur dioxide is around 60 or below.

Looking at the summary it looks like when there’s too little total sulfur dioxide it’s associated with low quality wines.

Since there could be a relationship between free sulfur dioxide and total sulfur dioxide, I’ll make a ratio between them to see if there’s an ideal ratio

df$free.total.sulfur <- df$free.sulfur.dioxide/df$total.sulfur.dioxide

It appears that as the ratio between free total sulfur dioxide to total sulfur dioxide increases, the quality increases. The best ratio observed is around 0.85.

Bivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed

Higher quality wines tend to have higher fixed acidity, lower volatile acidity, higher citric acid, lower density, higher pH, higher sulphate, and higher alcohol content when compared to medium and low quality wines.

Higher fixed acidity is associated with higher citric acid content, higher volatile acid content is associated with lower citric acid content, and higher fixed acidity content is associated with lower volatile acid content.

The quality in a wine peaks when the residual sugar is around 6 or between 8.5 and 10.5. Higher quality wines have less chlorides in general. Wines with a free sulfur dioxide content of around 55 have slightly higher qualities. The highest quality wines have a total sulfur dioxide content of 280-290 using median as the measure, though this is likely due to outliers. In general, a total sulfur dioxide of around 60 and below are ideal. As the ratio between free sulfur dioxide to total sulfur dioxide increases, the quality of wine increases, with the best observed ratio at around 0.85.

With the summaries, we saw that higher quality wines have more residual sugar, low quality wines have the least amount of free sulfur dioxide and total sulfur dioxide.

What was the strongest relationship you found?

Alcohol had the highest correlation for quality with a value of 0.5. The box plot showing alcohol and quality was the only box plot with the first quartile of the high quality group being around the same value of the 3rd quartile of the other two groups. This clearly shows that higher quality wines tend to have alcohol contents between 11 and 12 percent while low and medium quality wines are between 9.5 and 11.

There is also a strong relationship between low volatile acidity and high quality wine.

Multivariate Plots Section

Earlier we saw that quality increases as the ratio of free sulfur dioxide to total sulfur dioxide increases. We can see if the total sulfur dioxide in the wine also plays a role in quality or does only the ratio matter.

From the plot above it’s interesting to see that there are two almost parallel lines between the low quality and medium quality wine. The high quality line is nearly between the two lines, but does overlap with the low quality wines a little.

In bivariate analysis, we thought that having a higher ratio between free sulfur dioxide to total sulfur dioxide was better, but this is not the case.

In general, it seems that having a total sulfur dioxide of around 15 to 50 and free to total sulfur dioxide ratio between 0.15 to 0.75 results in highest quality wine. One thing to keep in mind is that these two depend on each other. In general, as the ratio between free and total sulfur dioxide increases, the total sulfur dioxide should decrease.

We found previously that higher quality wines is associated with higher residual sugar and more alcohol content. I know from common knowledge that low alcohol percent are the ones that tend to have high residual sugar. We can adjust for the effects of alcohol content and see if high quality wines still have more residual sugar. Since we also know that volatile acidity and chlorides decrease the quality of alcohol, we can see what happens to residual sugar when we adjust for those effects as well.

In bivariate analysis, we thought the quality peaked when residual sugar was around 6 or 8.5. We see that peak of 8.5 on the left side of this plot, but the quality is medium. After adjusting for alcohol content, High quality wines have the lowest amount of residual sugar compared to low and medium quality wines. Low quality wines tend to be high in residual sugar for the greatest range of alcohol content values.

After adjusting for volatile acidity, there is no clear relationship. It looks like high quality wines have more residual sugar than medium quality wines, but is split 50-50 between low quality wines.

After adjusting for chloride content in a wine, high quality wines tend to have more residual sugar compared to lower quality wines.

There was also a lot of correlation between fixed acidity, volatile acidity, and citric acid. We can examine what happens to the quality of wine when we adjust for each one the three acids and compare it to the other two acids.

Adjusting for fixed acidity, higher quality wines tend to have lower volatile acidity content and higher amount of citric compared to medium and low quality wines. Very high citric acid or volatile acidity is only associated with low quality wines.

Adjusting for citric acid, higher quality wines tend to have lower volatile acidity content compared to medium and low quality wines. Low quality wines have the highest volatile acidity content.There is no clear relationship of fixed acidity after adjusting for citric acid between the wine qualities. Low qualities wines just tend to have higher fixed acidity than medium and high quality wines.

Adjusting for volatile acidity, there is no clear relationship. It looks like high quality wines have higher fixed acidity and citric acid content compared to medium and low quality wines. This makes sense because higher fixed acidity and citric acid content is associated with higher quality wines.

I hypothesize that the density of the wine and sugar might be related. We previously found that higher wines tend to be a bit less dense but this could be due to that they have less sugar.

After adjusting for residual sugar, high quality wines tend to be less dense compared to medium quality wines but is split 50-50 between low quality wines.

We saw that higher pH was associated with higher wine quality, but this may be due to that higher quality wines have higher acid content.

After adjusting for acid content, it’s apparent that pH does not affect wine quality.

In bivariate analysis we didn’t see a straight forward relationship between chlorides and wine quality. We saw that chlorides have weak to weak-moderate correlations with citric acid, alcohol, sulphates, density, and pH. We know that pH and density doesn’t affect wine quality, but citric acid, alcohol, and sulphates do.

We will check what happens with chlorides when we adjust for each of these 3 variables.

After adjusting for citric acid, we find that higher quality wines have less chlorides.

After adjusting for alcohol, there is no clear relationship

After adjusting for sulphates, we find that higher quality wine have less chlorides.

Multivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed

High quality wine on average exhibit a total sulfur dioxide of between 15 to 50 depending on the ratio of free sulfur dioxide to total sulfur dioxide which should be between 0.15 and 0.75.

After adjusting for alcohol content, higher quality wines tend to have a low amount of residual sugar compared to lower quality wines. This is opposite of what we found earlier that high quality wine are associated with high residual sugar. After adjusting for chlorides, we did find that high quality wines have more residual sugar content compared to the other wine.

Adjusting for each of the three acids, we find that high quality wine is indeed associated with low volatile acidity, high fixed acidity, and high citric acid content.

In bivariate analysis we saw a clear trend that high quality wine was less dense compared to lower qualities. Here, we found that after adjusting for residual sugar, it is less dense compared to medium quality wines but only less dense half the time when compared to low quality wine.

After adjusting for acid content, pH does not affect wine quality

After adjusting for citric acid and sulphates, we find that high quality wine are associated with lower amounts of chloride.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?

The most surprising was finding the opposite compared to the bivariate analysis. For an example, we saw that more residual sugar on average meant higher wine quality. Here, we see that high quality wine have low amounts of residual sugar. There was also a surprise with the pH having nothing to do with wine quality. We also found that the ratio of free sulfur dioxide to total sulfur dioxide didn’t increase quality of wine as it increases, but having a certain total sulfur dioxide content paired with a certain ratio does increase wine quality.

Reflection

I started data exploration with univariate analysis on each chemical attribute of red wine. The data was tidy and each column had the correct data type.I found the distribution of every variable and under quality, I noticed that it could be separated into low, medium, and high quality wine based on the grouping of points.

With bivariate analysis, I found that higher quality wines are associated with higher fixed acidity, lower volatile acidity, higher citric acid, lower density, higher pH, higher sulphate, higher alcohol content, higher residual sugar, less chlorides, and total sulfur dioxide content between 15 and 50 with certain ratios of free sulfur dioxide to total sulfur dioxide from 0.15 to 0.75.

With multivariate analysis, some of the trends I found in bivariate were not completely true. Higher quality wines tend to have low residual sugar after taking into account the alcohol percentage of wines. After adjusting for acid content, pH does not affect wine quality.

Overall I noticed that the bivariate analysis is not completely reliable when you don’t adjust for certain variables. I did not look into every multivariate plot possible to see if there were other variables found to have a certain relationship under bivariate change under multivariate conditions.

There are several limitations to this analysis. The first one is that the way I defined the wine quality does not necessarily represent the high, medium, and low wine qualities, so trends found only rely on the original definition. High quality wine is rated 7 or 8. Medium quality is 5 or 6. Low quality is 3 or 4. The second limitation is that the data contains only Portugeuse “Vinho Verde” red wines, so the conclusions and trends found here only apply to those group of wines and not red wines in general. Another limitation could be the presence of lurking variables. For an example, the age of the wine could impact wine quality.There were also a lot of medium quality wine but not a lot of high quality wine or low quality wine, so the observations for some of the plots may have occurred due to chance.

For future work with this dataset, more multivariate analysis can be done. Instead of looking at just the different quality of wine, you could separate other variables into groups and compare it with quality and another variable. More variables could be included such as ratios between variables and create more complex visualizations that plot between two different ratios and find the ideal ratio of certain attributes. It could be the case that some attributes are not simple in that more is always better or less is always better. We saw that with free sulfur dioxide. We also saw that the three acid attributes were correlated with each other. Statistical models can also be created or machine learning models to predict wine quality based on the chemical attributes. Bootstrapping could be applied to the dataset to achieve higher counts of low quality and high quality wine. This could potentially change some of the trends found in this analysis.
